      {
        "type": "message",
        "time": "2026-03-25T15:10:00+08:00",
        "sender": "A",
        "content": "Sarah, while the idea of a 'unified' GCN for all cities is elegant, local driving cultures, traffic laws, and specific congestion bottlenecks make it difficult to generalize without massive data. Why not start with London? It has excellent open data (TfL) and a very complex graph. Also, your current model is text/sensor only. Have you considered multimodal factors like bike-sharing demand? It fluctuates wildly and affects car traffic."
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "conversation_id": "round_02_london_bikes",
    "participants": {
      "A": "Advisor (Dr. Schmidt)",
      "B": "Student (Sarah)"
    },
    "project": "Unified Graph Neural Network Architectures for Predictive Urban Traffic Analytics",
    "records": [
      {
        "type": "message",
        "time": "2026-03-27T09:00:00+08:00",
        "sender": "B",
        "content": "I've revised the proposal. I'm now focusing on a Spatial-Temporal GCN for London's bike-sharing system. I've integrated weather and holiday data into the feature set. f2.pdf contains the updated ST-GCN architecture."
      },
      {
        "type": "file",
        "time": "2026-03-27T09:01:00+08:00",
        "sender": "B",
        "content": "/Users/mgccvmacair/Myproject/Academic/ResearchProject/backend/projects/project03/files/f2.pdf"
      },
      {
        "type": "message",
        "time": "2026-03-27T16:30:00+08:00",
        "sender": "A",
        "content": "The ST-GCN in f2.pdf is a solid step forward. But it assumes a static road graph with fixed edge weights. In London, road segments go offline frequently, and 'importance' of a connection is dynamic. How will you handle sparse or failing sensors? A fixed GCN kernel will propagate errors. Consider moving towards an Adaptive Graph Attention mechanism (GAT)."
      }
    ]
  }
]
